<TEXT>
      ART
   <ORGANIZATION>National Museum of Women</ORGANIZATION> in the Arts, <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>: "American Women Artists, 1830-1930" -- The first <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> museum devoted solely to women artists opens with this exhibit of 124 paintings and sculptures from the late 19th and early 20th centuries. 
Included are works by <PERSON>Mary Cassatt</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Georgia O'Keeffe</ORGANIZATION>, and lesser-known talents such as <PERSON>Ellen Day Hale</PERSON> and portraitist <PERSON>Cecilia Beaux</PERSON>. 4590 <ORGANIZATION>MacArthur Boulevard</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>N.W. April</ORGANIZATION> 7-June 14. 
The show travels to the <ORGANIZATION>Minneapolis Institute of Arts</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>July 5-Aug</DATE>. 30; the <PERSON>Wadsworth Atheneum</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Hartford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Conn.</LOCATION>, <DATE>Sept. 19-Nov</DATE>. 15; the <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION> Museum of Art, <DATE>Dec. 5</DATE>, 1987-Jan. 31, <DATE>1988</DATE>; and the <ORGANIZATION>Meadows Museum</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION>, <DATE>Feb. 20-April 17, 1988</DATE>. 

   Dallas Museum of Art: "A Century of Modern Sculpture: The Patsy and <PERSON>Raymond Nasher</PERSON> Collection" -- Just over 100 works by 54 artists, including <PERSON>Rodin</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Matisse</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Picasso</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Brancusi</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Moore</PERSON>. 1717 <LOCATION>North Harwood</LOCATION>. 
<DATE>April 5-May 31</DATE>. 
Selections from the show move to <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>National Gallery of Art</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>June 28</DATE>, 1987-Jan. 3, <DATE>1988</DATE>. 

   <PERSON>Alexander F. Millikin Gallery</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>: Birds, flowering branches, snowy landscapes and a butterfly-and-leaf-covered temptress are some of the subjects featured in a rare show of "<LOCATION>Nihonga</LOCATION>" -- traditional Japanese-style paintings done on paper or silk and using only natural pigments and gold hammered so thin it becomes as transparent as a ray of sun. 98 <ORGANIZATION>Prince St. Through April 1</ORGANIZATION>. 

   <PERSON>Diane Brown Gallery</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>: "Fallen Limbs Rising" -- a collage of bronze castings and natural branches of extinct and endangered trees from the <ORGANIZATION>Northeast</ORGANIZATION> pays symbolic homage to the spirit of forests. 100 <ORGANIZATION>Greene St. Through April 8</ORGANIZATION>. 

   DANCE
   <ORGANIZATION>Laura Dean Dancers</ORGANIZATION> and Musicians: This intense, energetic troupe returns to <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION> after an eight-year absence with a double dose of Dean -- both choreography and music. 
The program includes the <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> premiere of "Magnetic," set to a dramatic synthesizer score. 
Joyce Theater, 175 Eighth Ave. (at 19th St.). 
April 7-12. (212) 242-0800. 

   Tibetan Opera, Music and Dance From Lhasa: A colorful spectacle marrying Indian drama with singing, makeup and movement styles reminiscent of Chinese opera -- <LOCATION>Stanford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Dinkelspiel Auditorium</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Stanford University</ORGANIZATION>), <DATE>March 26-27</DATE>; <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Zellerbach Hall</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION>), <DATE>March 28</DATE>; <LOCATION>Mendocino</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION> (Cotton Auditorium), <DATE>March 29</DATE>; <LOCATION>Pasadena</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Beckman Auditorium</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>California Institute of Technology</ORGANIZATION>), <DATE>March 31</DATE>; <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION> (<LOCATION>Mandeville Auditorium</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION>), <DATE>April 1</DATE>; <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION> (Performing Arts Theatre, <ORGANIZATION>University of California</ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION>Santa Cruz</ORGANIZATION>), <DATE>April 4</DATE>. (212) 288-6400, ext. 286. 

   MUSIC
   Metropolitan Opera: <PERSON>Maria Ewing</PERSON> puts on basic black as novice nun <ORGANIZATION>Blanche de la Force</ORGANIZATION> in a revival of <LOCATION>Poulenc</LOCATION>'s "The Dialogues of the Carmelites," while <PERSON>Marilyn Horne</PERSON> wields her shears wearing something more seductive for her role in <ORGANIZATION>Saint-Saen</ORGANIZATION>'s "Samson et Dalila." 
Tenor <PERSON>Jon Vickers</PERSON> sings the biblical hero. 
Lincoln Center, 65th and Broadway, <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>. 
"Dialogues" can be seen <DATE>March 27</DATE> and 30; <DATE>April 4</DATE>, 7 and 10. 
"Samson" runs <DATE>March 28</DATE> and 31; <DATE>April 3</DATE> and 8. (212) 799-3100. 

   <PERSON>Naoko Yoshino</PERSON>, a 20-year-old harpist and winner of the <DATE>1985</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Ninth International Harp Contest</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION>, makes her <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> debut. 
Her program includes <PERSON>Yuzo Toyama</PERSON>'s "Fantasy," <PERSON>Spohr</PERSON>'s "Fantasie in C minor, Op. 35," and <ORGANIZATION>Prokofiev</ORGANIZATION>'s "Prelude in C Major." 
<ORGANIZATION>Merkin Concert Hall</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Abraham Goodman House</ORGANIZATION>, 129 West 67th St., <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>. 
<DATE>March 31</DATE> at <TIME>2 p.m.</TIME> (212) 362-8719. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Houston Grand Opera</ORGANIZATION>: A new production of <PERSON>Richard Strauss</PERSON>'s "Salome" offers <PERSON>Josephine Barstow</PERSON>, with the seven veils and sets designed by artist <PERSON>Jim Dine</PERSON>. 
<PERSON>Rosalind Elias</PERSON> is Herodias; <ORGANIZATION>Ingvar Wixell</ORGANIZATION> sings <PERSON>Jochanaan</PERSON> and <PERSON>John DeMain</PERSON> conducts. 
<DATE>March 27, 28, 29</DATE> and 31; <DATE>April 1</DATE> and 3. (713) 227-ARTS. 

   Opera Company of <LOCATION>Philadelphia</LOCATION>: <PERSON>Paata Burchuladze</PERSON>, a bass from <LOCATION>Soviet Georgia</LOCATION>, makes his <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> opera debut as the crazy czar in the original <DATE>1869</DATE> version of <ORGANIZATION>Mussorgky</ORGANIZATION>'s "Boris Godunov." 
The Metropolitan Opera's <PERSON>Max Epstein</PERSON> conducts. 
Academy of Music, Broad and <LOCATION>Locust</LOCATION> streets. 
<DATE>March 30</DATE> and <DATE>April 3</DATE>. (215) 893-1930. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Chicago Opera Theater</ORGANIZATION> presents <PERSON>Britten</PERSON>'s "The Turn of the Screw." 
<PERSON>Claudia Cummings</PERSON>, <PERSON>Glenn Siebert</PERSON> and <PERSON>Diane Ragains</PERSON> star; <PERSON>Steven Larsen</PERSON> conducts. 
Athenaeum Theater, <DATE>2936</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>N. Southport Ave.</ORGANIZATION> <DATE>April 4</DATE>, 5, 8, 10-12 and 15. (312) 663-0048. 

   U2: This Irish rock band's tour is one of the most eagerly awaited on the pop calendar -- <LOCATION>Tempe</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ariz.</LOCATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Arizona State University</ORGANIZATION>), <DATE>April 2</DATE>; <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION> (The Summit), <DATE>April 7</DATE>; <LOCATION>Las Cruces</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.M.</LOCATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Pan American Center</ORGANIZATION>), <DATE>April 10</DATE>; <LOCATION>Las Vegas</LOCATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Thomas &amp; Mack Arena</ORGANIZATION>), <DATE>April 12</DATE>; <LOCATION>San Diego</LOCATION> (Sports Arena), <DATE>April 13-14</DATE>; <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> (Sports Arena), <DATE>April 17-18</DATE> and <DATE>20-22</DATE>. 

