<HEADLINE>  HAPPY GROOVE YEAR
BY DAVID PLOTNIKOFF  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  FRONT LINES  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     We do it because hunkering down in front of the tube while others make
merry seems like a slothful, downright cowardly  way to greet a new year full
of possibilities.;   We do it because we want -- and deserve -- to be
unshackled from yesterday's business. Shredding the calendar. Cleaning the
slate. End-ing the inning. Initiating a karma download. Closure, by whatever
name, is a comfort and a joy.;   Goodbye, <LOCATION>Gorby</LOCATION>. So long, <PERSON>Bill Graham</PERSON>. Happy
trails, <PERSON>Johnny Carson</PERSON>. That's a wrap, <PERSON>Willie Smith</PERSON>. Don't slam the door on
your way out, <PERSON>Kevin Mitchell</PERSON>. Thanks for stoppingby, <ORGANIZATION>Anita Hill</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>John Sununu</PERSON>
and <PERSON>Saddam Hussein</PERSON> -- your 15 minutes are up. Please clear the set and make
way for presidential primaries, Olympic heroes and post-Soviet Asia.;   Around
the bay, there are almost as many events as there are reasons to celebrate.
From thrash funk to Viennese opera, classic blues to big-name comedy, here are
some of best places to greet '92:;   Rock 'n' roll connoisseurs looking for
top-flight talent have some easy choices: X, probably <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>'s greatest
rock 'n' roll band of the <DATE>last decade</DATE>, has a rare reunion show at One Step
Beyond, <DATE>1400</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Martin Ave.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION>. Tickets are <MONEY>$25</MONEY> advance or at the door.
(408) 982-0555. The Grateful Dead's annual pageant of psychedelia at <ORGANIZATION>Oakland
Coliseum</ORGANIZATION> is sold out. The <ORGANIZATION>Neville Brothers</ORGANIZATION> bring the heartbeat of <LOCATION>New Orleans</LOCATION>
to the <ORGANIZATION>Warfield Theater</ORGANIZATION>, 982 Market St., <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>. Tickets are <MONEY>$28.50</MONEY> to
<MONEY>$30</MONEY>. (415) 775-7722. The <ORGANIZATION>Red Hot Chili Peppers</ORGANIZATION> top a funk-rockin' triple-bill
with Nirvana and <LOCATION>Pearl Jam</LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION>Cow Palace</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Daly City</LOCATION>. Tickets are <MONEY>$27.50</MONEY>
advance. (510) 762-2277. The <LOCATION>California Ballroom</LOCATION>, <PERSON>1736 Franklin St.</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION>,
has a killer blues-and-soul show featuring <PERSON>Solomon Burke</PERSON>, <PERSON>Dorothy Moore</PERSON>, <PERSON>Sam
Mayfield</PERSON> and the Soul's Alive Orchestra and <PERSON>Charles</PERSON> "Merry Christmas, Baby"
<PERSON>Brown</PERSON>. Tickets are <MONEY>$75</MONEY>. (510) 769-3701. Two other blues gigs worth considering
are local legend Taj Mahal at Slim's, 333 11th St., <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> (<MONEY>$50</MONEY>,
advance or at the door), (415) 255-0333, and hard-rockin'diva <PERSON>Etta James</PERSON> at
the <ORGANIZATION>Great American Music Hall</ORGANIZATION>, 859 <ORGANIZATION>O'Farrell St.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> (<MONEY>$55</MONEY>), (415)
885-0750. Latin-music aficionados have a hard call: <PERSON>Dr. Loco</PERSON>'s Rockin'
Jalapeno Band cuts loose at <LOCATION>Longshoremen</LOCATION>'s <PERSON>Hall</PERSON>, 400 <ORGANIZATION>North Point</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION>. Tickets are <MONEY>$25</MONEY>. (415) 776-8999. Alberto's, <ORGANIZATION>Mountain View</ORGANIZATION>'s hot new
Latin dance club at 736 <PERSON>Dana St.</PERSON>, has a Brazilian dance party with <ORGANIZATION>Terra Sul</ORGANIZATION>
and <ORGANIZATION>Samba Time</ORGANIZATION>. Tickets are <MONEY>$25</MONEY>. (415) 968-3007.;   For the middle-brow crowd,
there's <PERSON>Huey Lewis</PERSON> and the News at the <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> Civic Auditorium. Tickets
