<DESCRIPT>  SUMMER; MUSIC; FESTIVAL; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  PACK up a picnic, sun hat, parka (just in case) and tanning lotion. It's time
for your summer music festival fix.;    In addition to the well-publicized
Paul Masson, Villa Montalvo and Shoreline concerts, there are other music
festivals here and around the region that offer something for every taste.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CONCERTS FAR AND WIDE
REGIONAL FEASTS CELEBRATE THE ARTS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Music Festivals  </MEMO>
<TEXT>   SANTA CLARA COUNTY;    <ORGANIZATION>Midsummer Mozart Festival</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>July 10-Aug</DATE>. 4, a movable
feast. Conductor <PERSON>George Cleve</PERSON> migrates with his all-Mozart orchestral programs
through <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Flint Center</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION>, plus some <PERSON>Villa
Montalvo</PERSON> dates. Soloists <PERSON>Ivan Moravec</PERSON>, <PERSON>Andre Watts</PERSON>, <PERSON>Daniel Kobialka</PERSON>, and
<PERSON>Melvyn Tan</PERSON>. (408) 864-8816, (415) 762-2277.;    Festival of the Arts, <ORGANIZATION>Foothill
College</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Los Altos Hills</LOCATION>, through <DATE>Aug. 18</DATE>. A little of everything by area
companies, from "Carousel" to "The Merry Widow" to a rare staging of <ORGANIZATION>Verdi</ORGANIZATION>'s
opera "Jerusalem" and a Mozart "Requiem" sing-along too. Prices in the <MONEY>$2</MONEY>-<MONEY>$20</MONEY>
range. (415) 948-4444.;  <LOCATION>SANTA CRUZ AREA</LOCATION>;    <ORGANIZATION>Cabrillo Music Festival</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>July
25-Aug</DATE>. 4. Composer-conductor <PERSON>John</PERSON> ("Nixon in <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>") <PERSON>Adams</PERSON> leads this year's
event as the migrating fest on the coast pulls into <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>'s newly
renovated 970-seat Civic Auditorium. The highly laid-back, informal orchestral
festival is the <LOCATION>West Coast</LOCATION>'s most adventurous one in 20th-century music.
Soloists: <PERSON>Stephanie Chase</PERSON>, <PERSON>Richard Goode</PERSON>, <PERSON>JoAnn Falletta</PERSON> and <PERSON>Dora Ohrenstein</PERSON>.
There's the usual excursion to Mission San <PERSON>Juan Bautista</PERSON>. (408) 429-3444.;   
<ORGANIZATION>Carmel Bach Festival</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>July 15-Aug</DATE>. 4. This is the most sentimental journey of
the <DATE>summer</DATE>, with <PERSON>Conductor Sandor Salgo</PERSON>, heading the rituals for 36 years,
stepping down this <DATE>August</DATE>. A heavy dose of Mozart this year, including "The
Magic Flute." (408) 624-2046.;  <LOCATION>SAN FRANCISCO</LOCATION>;    <ORGANIZATION>Mozart &amp; His Time</ORGANIZATION>, a
citywide festival through <DATE>June 30</DATE>. The vast program of more than 50 events and
150 performances includes concerts, opera, lectures, views of mental health,
zany quasi-Mozartian inventions. (408) 998-2277.;    <ORGANIZATION>Chamber Music West</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>June
3-15</DATE>. The <ORGANIZATION>S.F. Conservatory of Music</ORGANIZATION> hosts near-nightly changing concerts, to
include the <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION> String Quartet, <PERSON>Stuart Canin</PERSON>, Hai-Ye Ni, <PERSON>David Krehbiel</PERSON>.
There are digressions to <LOCATION>Saratoga</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION>. (408) 741-3428, (415)
665-0874.;    <ORGANIZATION>Stern Grove Festival</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>June 16-Aug</DATE>. 18. This outdoor park stage
has the greatest weather extremes, but it's all free, every <DATE>Sunday</DATE> at <TIME>2 p.m.</TIME>,
unreserved seating and picnic space. Highlights: <ORGANIZATION>Preservation Hall Jazz Band</ORGANIZATION>,
Afro-Cuban bands, <LOCATION>S.F. Ballet</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>S.F. Symphony</LOCATION>, opera, <PERSON>Gilbert and Sullivan</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Smetana</PERSON>'s "The Bartered Bride." For season brochure, send an addressed,
stamped envelope to the fest at 44 Page St., <ORGANIZATION>Suite</ORGANIZATION> 604D, <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> 94102.;
   Pocket Opera, <ORGANIZATION>PG&amp;E Beale St. Theater</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>Sundays</DATE> through <DATE>June 23</DATE>. The
funniest, most intimate opera company dreamed up by <PERSON>Donald Pippin</PERSON> roars back
with "The Secret Marriage," "The Barber of <LOCATION>Seville</LOCATION>," "The Marriage of Figaro"
and a modern-day adaptation of "The Abduction from the Seraglio." (415)
989-1855.;  FARTHER AFIELD;    <ORGANIZATION>Hollywood Bowl Summer Festival</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>July 3-Sept</DATE>.
21. This <DATE>summer</DATE> ritual with amplification and 15,000 folks a night is famous.
The <ORGANIZATION>L.A. Philharmonic</ORGANIZATION> holds forth, with everyone from <PERSON>Simon Rattle</PERSON> to <PERSON>Henry
Mancini</PERSON>, <PERSON>Itzhak Perlman</PERSON> to Miles <PERSON>Davis</PERSON>. New this year is the conductor that
the San Jose Symphony almost snagged, <PERSON>John Mauceri</PERSON>, as director of the new
<ORGANIZATION>Hollywood Bowl Orchestra</ORGANIZATION>. (213) 850-2000.;    <ORGANIZATION>Bear Valley Festival</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>July
27-Aug</DATE>. 11. The 7,000-foot altitude adds to the exhilaration as <ORGANIZATION>Carter Nice</ORGANIZATION>
leads his seventh season. Orchestral concerts with pianist <PERSON>Ursula Oppens</PERSON>, plus
the opera "Carmen" with <PERSON>Hilda Harris</PERSON>. (209) 753-2574.;  WESTERN STATES;   
<ORGANIZATION>Oregon Bach Festival</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Eugene</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Ore.</LOCATION>, <DATE>June</DATE> 23-July 7. The northerly <PERSON>Bach</PERSON> fest is
as eclectic as <LOCATION>Carmel</LOCATION>'s, but with the German orientation of conductor-scholar
<PERSON>Helmut Rilling</PERSON> at the helm. The 22nd season features mezzo <PERSON>Frederica von
Stade</PERSON>, pianist <PERSON>Jeffrey Kahane</PERSON>, and the three trumpeter brothers Laubin from
<LOCATION>Germany</LOCATION>. Also the Latvian chorus <PERSON>Ave Sol</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>N.Y. Baroque Dance Co.</ORGANIZATION>, and the
<LOCATION>Angeles Quartet</LOCATION>, in this spectrum of <LOCATION>Bach</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Mozart</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Mendelssohn</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Dvorak</PERSON> (the
latter via the opera "<PERSON>Dimitrij</PERSON>," in concert version). (503) 346-5666.;   
<ORGANIZATION>Seattle Opera Summer</ORGANIZATION> (<PERSON>Wagner</PERSON>) Festival, <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Wash.</LOCATION>, <DATE>Aug. 3-24, 1990</DATE>. After
years of hiatus, <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION> gamely cranked up again its mighty <PERSON>Wagner</PERSON> "Ring"
tetralogy, more than 16 hours of myth and man -- and super-women, too --
sprawling over four days, with casts not on a plane with what <LOCATION>San Franciscans</LOCATION>
are used to. But <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> has discontinued its every-five-years "Ring"
sequence, thus <LOCATION>Seattle</LOCATION>'s "Ring" wins the Western states by default. Using the
<DATE>1986</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Robert Israel</ORGANIZATION> production, it features stage director <PERSON>Francois Rochaix</PERSON>,
conductor <PERSON>Hermann Michael</PERSON>. (206) 443-4711.;    <ORGANIZATION>Santa Fe</ORGANIZATION> (<LOCATION>N.M.</LOCATION>) Chamber Music
Festival, <DATE>July 7-Aug</DATE>. 19. This year the multitude of programs highlight
<PERSON>Shostakovich</PERSON> and his Russian brethren. Chamber music galore, yes -- but with
the spice of <PERSON>Mozart</PERSON>'s first opera, "<PERSON>Bastien</PERSON> and Bastienne" (<DATE>July 11</DATE>, 13).
(505) 983-2075.  </TEXT>
