<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EYE OPENERS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>  WHEN/WHERE: One-hour family performance, 7 tonight; regular performance, <TIME>8
p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Saturday</DATE>. Mountain View Center for the Performing Arts. Also, <TIME>8 p.m.</TIME>
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, Performing Arts Theater, UC-Santa Cruz.; HOW MUCH: <MONEY>$5</MONEY> (children 12
and under), <MONEY>$7.50</MONEY> (adults) at family performance; <MONEY>$20</MONEY> for <DATE>Saturday</DATE> show. (415)
903-6000. In <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>, <MONEY>$12</MONEY>, <MONEY>$10</MONEY> students/seniors. (408) 459-2159.; WHY:
After mastering the traditional songs of Plains and woodland tribes, <PERSON>R. Carlos
Nakai</PERSON> began developing an individual style, using the American Indian flute in
a jazz ensemble, composing music for the <ORGANIZATION>Martha Graham Dance Company</ORGANIZATION> and
recording for Canyon Records.; THE GENUINE DIAMELLES; WHEN/WHERE: <TIME>10 p.m.</TIME>
<DATE>Saturday</DATE>, <LOCATION>Hotel Utah</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>San Francisco.</LOCATION>; HOW MUCH: <MONEY>$3</MONEY>; (415) 421-8308; WHY:
Superlative a cappella pop that runs the gamut from "The Peer Gynt Suite" and
Boy Scout camp songs to <ORGANIZATION>Led Zeppelin</ORGANIZATION> and the theme to "Sesame Street."; 'THE
GIN GAME'; Deaf West Theater Company.; WHEN/WHERE: <TIME>7:30 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Tuesday-Friday</DATE>,
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> School for the Deaf, 39350 <ORGANIZATION>Gallaudet Drive</ORGANIZATION>, Fremont.; HOW MUCH:
<MONEY>$4</MONEY>-<MONEY>$12</MONEY>; (510) 895-2430.; WHY: This is a contrived two-character play -- but
not when the dialogue is translated into American Sign Language by the great
<PERSON>Phyllis Frelich</PERSON>, who won a Tony for "Children of a Lesser God."; SAN JOSE
SYMPHONY; Under guest conductor <PERSON>Gabriel Chmura.</PERSON>; WHEN/WHERE: <TIME>8:30
tonight-Saturday</TIME>, Center for the Performing Arts, <ORGANIZATION>Almaden Boulevard</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Park
Avenue</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>; also <TIME>2:30 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Flint Center</ORGANIZATION>, De Anza College,
<LOCATION>Cupertino.</LOCATION>; HOW MUCH: <MONEY>$9</MONEY>-<MONEY>$37</MONEY>; (408) 998-2277 or (415) 762-2277.; WHY: Born in
<LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION> and an Israeli citizen, <PERSON>Chmura</PERSON> is an exciting international talent. He
is joined by <PERSON>Franklin Larey</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Mozart</LOCATION>'s Piano Concerto No. 23 in A Major.; <LOCATION>SAN
FRANCISCO OPERA</LOCATION>; WHEN/WHERE: "Elektra" opens <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, "Attila" opens
<DATE>Thursday</DATE>. <ORGANIZATION>Opera House</ORGANIZATION>, Van Ness Avenue and <ORGANIZATION>Grove Street</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>.
Through <DATE>Dec. 8.</DATE>; HOW MUCH: <MONEY>$28</MONEY>-<MONEY>$85</MONEY>; (415) 431-5400.; WHY: <PERSON>Richard Strauss</PERSON>'
violently obsessive "Elektra" (sung in German) features the Wagnerian soprano
from <LOCATION>Wales</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Gwyneth Jones</LOCATION>, in the title role. Starring as <LOCATION>Attila</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Verdi</LOCATION>'s
early gem of the same name (sung in Italian) is the swashbuckling bass <PERSON>Samuel
Ramey</PERSON>, who also has recorded the work with distinction. Supertitle projections
make it all linguistically painless.; 'SIGHTINGS'; <LOCATION>Oakland Ballet.</LOCATION>;
WHEN/WHERE: 8 <DATE>tonight-Saturday</DATE> and <TIME>2 p.m.</TIME> <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Paramount Theater</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>2025
Broadway</LOCATION>, Oakland.; HOW MUCH: <MONEY>$5</MONEY>-<MONEY>$28</MONEY>. (510) 465-6400.; WHY: In her first
ballet, <PERSON>Margaret Jenkins</PERSON>, whose contemporary choreography is a mix of the
cerebral and the sensual, discovers angels all around us. The Kronos Quartet
plays, live, a new score by Australian composer <PERSON>Peter Sculthorpe.</PERSON>; RETURN OF
THE YOUNG GALLERY; WHEN/WHERE: Reception, 5-8 tonight, 307 No. <LOCATION>Santa Cruz
Ave.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Los Gatos.</LOCATION>; HOW MUCH: Free; (408) 399-1900.; WHY: A <LOCATION>South Bay</LOCATION> perennial,
the 20-year-old <ORGANIZATION>Young Gallery</ORGANIZATION> never really disappeared. But because it jumped
from one location to another -- through no fault of its own; blame
redevelopment and an earthquake -- it was sometimes hard to track. Now it's
back in business, purveying art with a contemporary beat. The opening show,
"Young-Again," includes gallery steadies <PERSON>John Battenberg</PERSON>, <PERSON>Fletcher Benton</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Gary Bukovnik</PERSON>, <PERSON>Beth Van Hoesen</PERSON>, <PERSON>Theodore Waddell</PERSON> and <PERSON>Reid Winfrey</PERSON>.  </TEXT>
