<DESCRIPT>  THEATER; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE Asian population is booming in California -- and the nation -- the census
takers tell us.;    The theater is going to make the most of it. Immediately.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Weekend  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ASIAN PLAYS GAIN THEATERS' ATTENTION  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Theater  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The Mountain View Center for the Performing Arts is bringing the
Asian-American acting company, <ORGANIZATION>Pan Asian Repertory</ORGANIZATION>, to its spanking new
facility <DATE>March 14</DATE> through 16.;    The company is presenting <PERSON>Wakako Yamauchi</PERSON>'s
play, "And the Soul Shall Dance," set in the <LOCATION>Imperial Valley of California</LOCATION> at
the end of the Depression. A <DATE>1977</DATE> production of the play in <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> won
three <ORGANIZATION>LA Drama Critics Awards</ORGANIZATION>. The play has been revived and had a successful
run most recently in <LOCATION>New York.</LOCATION>;    "And the Soul Shall Dance," called an Asian
"Grapes of Wrath" by some critics, has apparently become more daring in its
new production, including more sensual material. That's according to director
<PERSON>Kati Kuroda</PERSON>, who seems to know the magic words in attracting an audience.;   
Meanwhile, TheatreWorks in <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION> readies a new production of the classic,
"Rashomon," at the <ORGANIZATION>Lucie Stern Theater</ORGANIZATION>, to run <DATE>March 16 through April 6</DATE>, after
previews <DATE>March 14</DATE> and 15.;    The play, written by <PERSON>Fay</PERSON> and <PERSON>Michael Kanin</PERSON> from
the ancient stories by <PERSON>Akutagawa</PERSON>, will have an all-Asian cast locally. There
was a Broadway production in <DATE>1959</DATE> and an <PERSON>Akira Kurosawa</PERSON> film after that.;   
In <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION> the play will be directed by <PERSON>Yuriko Doi</PERSON>, who is artistic director
of <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>'s Theatre of Yugen.;    Add to this an upcoming San Jose
Civic Light Opera production of <PERSON>Stephen Sondheim</PERSON>'s "Pacific Overtures," <DATE>May 16</DATE>
to <DATE>June 11</DATE>. The show, with a mostly Asian cast, deals with <ORGANIZATION>American Commodore
Perry</ORGANIZATION>'s "opening" of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> to international trade.;    Finally, the hit
British musical "Miss Saigon" is readying previews on Broadway, with an
opening set for <DATE>April 11</DATE>. "Pacific Overtures" and "Miss Saigon" are Broadway
shows with Asian themes and not Asian shows themselves. However, as interest
in the themes grows, along with the Asian population, it's a good bet we will
be getting more Asian-oriented productions in our theaters, and soon.;   
<LOCATION>Burgeoning Flint</LOCATION>;  <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Flint Center</ORGANIZATION> seems poised to get a lot more
theater on its stage. <PERSON>Vicki O'Brien</PERSON>, who manages the <LOCATION>Flint</LOCATION> schedule, is in
discussions with the <PERSON>James Nederlander</PERSON> theater people in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> concerning
the possibility of bringing the hit musical "Grand Hotel" to <LOCATION>Flint</LOCATION>. The show
was supposed to play <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, but a rift between the <PERSON>Carole Hays
Shorenstein</PERSON> office and <ORGANIZATION>Nederlander</ORGANIZATION> has scratched that run. So it may play
<LOCATION>Flint</LOCATION> for a week in <DATE>August</DATE>. The only holdup is cost.;    Also possible for
<ORGANIZATION>Flint Center</ORGANIZATION> is a new production of "Annie" with <PERSON>Gretchen Wyler</PERSON> and <PERSON>John
Schuck</PERSON>, the first week in <DATE>June</DATE>, and yet another production of "My Fair Lady"
with <PERSON>Neil Harrison</PERSON> or <PERSON>Richard Chamberlain.</PERSON>;    <PERSON>O'Brien</PERSON> says that recent
productions of "Cats," "The Phantom of the Opera" (non-Broadway version) and
"A Chorus Line" have all done extremely well in <LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION>, leading to thoughts
of expanding the theater schedule.;    The Theater Beat;  <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION> needs
more theater, especially during the bulk of the year when <ORGANIZATION>Shakespeare Santa
Cruz</ORGANIZATION> is hibernating. The <ORGANIZATION>Santa Cruz Actors Theater</ORGANIZATION> is trying to fill the
vacuum, with two original one-act comedies, "Yesterday's Paper" and "Citizen
<PERSON>Klein</PERSON>," on tap <DATE>March 15 through April 14</DATE> at 1001 Center St. . . . <PERSON>Philip
Slater</PERSON>, a local playwright, is the author . . . <PERSON>Rick Reynolds</PERSON>, a local comic,
is very hot stuff in the stand-up trade. His "Only the Truth Is Funny,"
opening a new run at the Theater on the Square in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> <DATE>March 5
through 31</DATE>, goes to <LOCATION>Broadway</LOCATION> this <DATE>spring</DATE>. Quite a leap . . .  </TEXT>
