<HEADLINE>  THE VERY SPECIAL F/X OF SAN JOSE NIGHTLIFE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Clubs  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  Admission: <MONEY>$3</MONEY>-<MONEY>$5.</MONEY>; Details: Dancing; Thursdays-Sundays, <TIME>9 p.m.</TIME> Live; music
<DATE>Wednesdays</DATE>, 10 p.m.; (408) 298-9796; CLUBS; The very special F/X; of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>
nightlife; FIVE years ago, <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> had a downtown that could rival <LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION> in
terms of sheer destruction. The only difference was that life after dark in
<LOCATION>Beirut</LOCATION> was much more interesting. Now, more than a half-decade of aggressive
redevelopment has given the <LOCATION>Garden City</LOCATION> a downtown full of gracious,
broad-shouldered new buildings and inviting public spaces. And still the
question lingers: Is this a two-night-per-week party town or what?;    It's
not supposed to be like this any more. Nightlife was . . . In The Plan. It's
almost as if the architects of the New Downtown paused to admire their
handiwork in the rosy glow of a weekday sunset, looked at each other and said
"Oh, great. I thought you were bringing the boulevardiers and bon vivants . .
.";    A recent <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, <TIME>10 p.m.</TIME>: The Oasis, the <ORGANIZATION>Heartthrob</ORGANIZATION> and the
<ORGANIZATION>Cactus Club</ORGANIZATION> are all line-less and listless. Marsugi's is flat-out dead, with
three people hunched at the bar. On First Street, between the <LOCATION>Pavilion</LOCATION> and the
Fairmont, the only souls afoot are a lone jogger and a man blowing dust in
little circles with a leaf-blower.;    But there is a flicker of light in this
weeknight wasteland: F/X. By 10:30, a hipper-than-thou collection of 45
underground-rock aficionados -- out-of-work local musicians, unreconstructed
punks and disaffected post-collegiate neo-Bohemians -- is milling about the
club's shoebox-shaped main room, waiting to see <PERSON>Helen Keller</PERSON> Plaid and the
<ORGANIZATION>Frontier Wives</ORGANIZATION>. In an hour, the crowd will swell to more than 100. With a
dirt-cheap <MONEY>$3</MONEY> cover for two of the <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION>'s finest club bands, this is the
place to be on this particular <DATE>Wednesday.</DATE>;    The basic
I-Have-A-Marketing-Degree-I-Just-Look-Like-A-Skate-Thug aesthetic is much in
evidence: Young men with slick hair, ratty plaid shirts, black T-shirts and
baggy shorts. Young women with black tights, T-shirts, tattoos and serious
boots. In other words -- it was a nice crowd. Several of the men sport
scraggly little beards, knee-length dungarees, porkpie hats and work boots --
as if they had just stepped out of a Depression-era <ORGANIZATION>Walker Evans</ORGANIZATION> photo. Let us
pray Madison Avenue doesn't get wind of the <LOCATION>Joad Look.</LOCATION>;    The year-old club
has tried to bring innovative theater, film, dance and fashion programs to the
First Street scene with limited success. Nevertheless, the club seems to have
a strong sense of identity. And the owners seem to harbor the all-too-rare
belief that clientele -- not six-for-a-dollar schnapps specials or other
gimmicks -- is what makes a scene.;    At 10:45 the four surly youths in <PERSON>Helen
Keller</PERSON> Plaid come out fighting like a mad mother bear. Soon, the dance floor
is half-full, with 50 people just absorbing the sonic wave. The band's
brilliant Velvet-Underground-Meets-the-Replacements-on-Mars set is sweet and
strong -- the mailed fist shielding the tender heart.;    The world-weary
looks of the clubhounds melt. Dancing, hugging, beer-spilling and random
collisions occur under the strobe light. It's as if the audience's collective
memory begins to wake: This is the good stuff. This is the sound we heard and
the way we felt that very first time -- when punk rock swooped us up and
turned us into sweaty, grinning idiots.;    It was like that for the <ORGANIZATION>Frontier
Wives</ORGANIZATION>, too. San Jose's oldest alternative rock band was in fine form -- from
"Elvis Was a Spy" right through "<PERSON>Louis Pasteur</PERSON>," a tender tale of how the
great scientist learned the secret of bacteria from a witch doctor. This is
the good stuff. One-hundred-and-ten decibels of earwax-melting,
speaker-shredding rock 'n' roll -- with heart and brains and brawn.;    This
home-brewed music is rude, inelegant and not even remotely upscale. When the
city fathers envisioned glittering nightlife, it's unlikely they were thinking
of the <ORGANIZATION>Frontier Wives</ORGANIZATION>. But the native flame is hard to snuff. Smother it with
zoning restrictions and license requirements and noise abatement acts, and
still it burns.;    <LOCATION>Winterland</LOCATION>, <DATE>1978</DATE>. The <ORGANIZATION>Mabuhay Gardens</ORGANIZATION>, <DATE>1981</DATE>. One Step
Beyond, <DATE>1986</DATE>. The Laundry Works <DATE>1987</DATE>. And now, in the wee hours of a <DATE>Thursday</DATE>
morning in the heart of the new <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, still it burns.  </TEXT>
