<LEADPARA>  ALTHOUGH my editors over at World Headquarters think of Santa Cruz as a suburb
of San Jose, most of us here in Surf City realize we are, in fact, part of
Greater Honolulu. I suspect that I'm one of many Santa Cruzans who make more
visits to and spend more time in Hawaii every year than San Jose -- as lovely
and nearby as the Garden City may be.;    Having just returned from what must
have been my 18th or 19th visit to the Islands, I thought I'd update you on
what's been going on in Honolulu and environs in recent days.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LEI ASIDE SURF CITY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     WE got there just as the tail end of Hurricane Fefa was petering out in the
<LOCATION>mid-Pacific</LOCATION>. It brought some rain, followed by one of those bouts of muggy
<LOCATION>Kona</LOCATION> weather with no cooling trade winds to keep things comfortable. My pal
<PERSON>Rick Carroll</PERSON>, who used to work for this newspaper and now writes and does
public relations on <LOCATION>Oahu</LOCATION>, put a good spin on the hot, humid day, though. "It's
like a good day in <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION>," he opined.;    <PERSON>Rick</PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON>Marcie</PERSON>, used to
be locals over here. Rick lived in <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION> and worked in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> for the
<ORGANIZATION>Chronicle</ORGANIZATION> after leaving the <ORGANIZATION>Mercury</ORGANIZATION>. Marcie also worked at the <ORGANIZATION>Chron</ORGANIZATION> after
some years as a reporter for the <ORGANIZATION>Monterey Peninsula Herald</ORGANIZATION>. Both have a lot of
friends in <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, and both asked me to pass along their
alohas.;    <PERSON>Rick Carroll</PERSON>, you might recall, uncovered the yarn about <PERSON>Marty</PERSON> the
<PERSON>Marijuana Mouse</PERSON>, the rodent who supposedly was gnawing his way through the
evidence locker at the <ORGANIZATION>San Jose Police Department</ORGANIZATION> a decade or so ago.;   
Soon, <PERSON>Rick</PERSON>'s latest book, on the great outdoor adventures of <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION>, will be
published in <LOCATION>San Francisco.</LOCATION>;    Strolling along Kalakaua Avenue each day, on
the way to the shave ice stand at the <ORGANIZATION>Royal Hawaiian Shopping Center</ORGANIZATION>, I
discovered an alarming trend that won't, I hope, make it to the mainland,
especially to <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>: large numbers of young men prowling the sidewalks
with giant parrots on their shoulders. I think some of the guys who used to
hand out time-share brochures or <ORGANIZATION>Hare Krishna</ORGANIZATION> tracts must have had midlife
career changes and gotten into birds instead.;    (There are, of course, some
shave ice outlets in <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>, but so far none has seemed authentic to me.
Instead of shaving little flakes from a big block of ice, the new machines
here -- and, unfortunately, at some Hawaiian locales as well -- seem to crush
ice cubes instead. The resulting heap of slush doesn't hold the flavored
syrups as well as the genuine article -- "da kine," as they would say in
pidgin.);    ANYWAY, there have always been one or two guys with colorful
macaws standing along <LOCATION>Kalakaua</LOCATION>. Their shtick is to befriend tourists, then
charge the rubes a couple of bucks if they want to take a picture of
themselves with the parrot as a prop.;    (A frighteningly high proportion of
the tourist population seems willing to part with cash in order to get a
snapshot of Mom with a large bird on her shoulder.);    A positive trend is
showing up in the Hawaiian shirt business. Aloha shirtmakers, led by the folks
at <ORGANIZATION>Paradise Found</ORGANIZATION>, are using fabrics that look and feel so much like the
material used during the heydays of the <DATE>1940s</DATE> and <DATE>'50s</DATE> that there's really no
need anymore to look at expensive antique garments. (A good aloha shirt from
the <DATE>'40s</DATE> can run you <MONEY>several hundred dollars</MONEY> in <LOCATION>Honolulu</LOCATION> these days. I know; I
collect Hawaiian shirts the way some people collect baseball cards.);    As
always, <LOCATION>Hawaii</LOCATION> calls. I consider it my home away from home. When I win the
lotto, you'll probably find me in the Islands as often as in <LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>. I'll
be the guy in the <ORGANIZATION>Mercury News</ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION>Honolulu</LOCATION> bureau, covering things for our
readers in <LOCATION>Surf City.</LOCATION>;    In the meantime, aloha!  </TEXT>
