<DESCRIPT>  OBITUARY; COLLECTIBLE; PERIODICAL; PUBLISHING; SANTA-CRUZ; MAN  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Magazine publisher John Conrad Finsand was an avid bicyclist who almost always
wore a helmet.;   But last Thursday, as he pedaled along East Cliff Drive only
blocks from his Santa Cruz home, Mr. Finsand was without a helmet. It cost him
his life.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JOHN FINSAND OF SANTA CRUZ, 36, PUBLISHER, AVID
BICYCLIST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     A parked motorist opened his car door directly in <PERSON>Mr. Finsand</PERSON>'s path. The
resulting crash cracked <PERSON>Mr. Finsand</PERSON>'s skull and caused a blood clot that later
contributed to his death, despite two surgical attempts to save him. He was
36.;   <PERSON>Mr. Finsand</PERSON>, said one of his friends, was "an outrageously
in-love-with-life person.";   "He was full of sass and pizazz and could jolly
anybody into anything," said <PERSON>Patricia Carney</PERSON>. "He was one of those people who
can walk into any room and lift everybody's spirits and be able to talk to
anyone.";   <PERSON>Mr. Finsand</PERSON> also loved music and poetry, running, swimming, yoga
and cooking. Friends credited him with the world's greatest recipe for
vegetarian pizza. In the last year <PERSON>Mr. Finsand</PERSON> had volunteered countless hours
to <ORGANIZATION>EarthSave</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Santa</LOCATION> Cruz-based environmental organization, and recently had
put together that group's soon-to-be published book catalog.;   But <PERSON>Mr.
Finsand</PERSON>'s first interest was "Antiques and Fine Arts," the magazine he founded
in <DATE>1980</DATE>. Editor and publisher Finsand nursed the publication from a 12-page
black-and-white newspaper to a nationally circulated, lavishly presented,
glossy production published six times annually.;   When he died, <PERSON>Mr. Finsand</PERSON>
had been working on the premier issue of "Art and Money," a new magazine
scheduled for publication in <LOCATION>December.</LOCATION>;   Though a <LOCATION>Minnesota</LOCATION> native, <PERSON>Mr.
Finsand</PERSON> graduated from <ORGANIZATION>Urbandale High School</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Iowa</LOCATION>. He served in the <ORGANIZATION>U.S.
Air Force</ORGANIZATION> from <DATE>1974</DATE> to <DATE>1978</DATE>, then attended <ORGANIZATION>San Jose State University</ORGANIZATION> and
worked for IBM.;   <PERSON>Mr. Finsand</PERSON> managed "The Feel," a <LOCATION>Los Gatos</LOCATION> rock band, in
<DATE>1981</DATE> and produced an album with the band. He also owned and operated the <LOCATION>Los
Gatos</LOCATION> Art Gallery for two years and was a board member of the <ORGANIZATION>Los Gatos Arts
Commission</ORGANIZATION> in the early 1980s.;   "He just had boundless energy," <PERSON>Carney</PERSON>
said.; (box)Born: <DATE>July 15, 1955</DATE>, <LOCATION>Moorhead</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Minn.</LOCATION>; (box)Died: <DATE>Sept. 28, 1991</DATE>,
<LOCATION>Santa Cruz</LOCATION>; (box)Survived by: Parents, Marye and <PERSON>Bud Finsand</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Versailles</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Ky.</LOCATION>; sisters, <PERSON>Kathryn Finsand</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Minnetonka</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Minn.</LOCATION>, and <PERSON>Nikki Bojanski</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Grapevine</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>; brother, <PERSON>Thomas Finsand</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Versailles</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ky.</LOCATION>; brother-in-law,
<PERSON>Tom Bojanski</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Grapevine</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION>; aunt and uncle, Dr. and <PERSON>Mrs. Theodore
Sielaff</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>; niece and nephew, <PERSON>John Mark</PERSON> and <PERSON>Andrea Marie Bojanski</PERSON> of
<LOCATION>Grapevine</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Texas.</LOCATION>; (box)Services: Noon <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> at <ORGANIZATION>Unity Temple</ORGANIZATION>, 407 Broadway,
<LOCATION>Santa Cruz.</LOCATION>; (box)Memorial: Family requests contributions to <ORGANIZATION>EarthSave
Foundation</ORGANIZATION>, 706 <PERSON>Frederick St.</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Santa Cruz 95062</LOCATION>  </TEXT>
